{
  "text": "Lysosomes-Because ADA activity has been detected in lysosomes [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , loss of ADA presumably leads to adenosine accumulation in lysosomes. To explore the role of adenosine in lysosomes, we first measured the level of adenosine in lysosomes isolated from human skin fibroblasts using high performance liquid chromatography (HPLC) [CITATION_3] . We detected significant amounts of adenosine and ATP in the lysosomes of human fibroblasts. With the calculation method we described before [CITATION_4] , the concentrations of lysosomal adenosine and ATP were estimated to be ϳ0.3-3 and ϳ0.2-2 mM, respectively. The concentration of lysosomal ATP obtained here using HPLC is in agreement with the value we reported previously using an ATP bioluminescence assay [CITATION_5] . Next, we compared the amount of lysosomal ATP and adenosine between wildtype (WT) human fibroblasts and ADA Ϫ/Ϫ human fibroblasts derived from an ADA-SCID patient that contain very low ADA activity [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] . Interestingly, although the ATP level is not different between WT and ADA Ϫ/Ϫ human fibroblasts ( Fig. 1,  A and B) , the lysosomal adenosine level was significantly increased in ADA Ϫ/Ϫ cells (Fig. 1 , A and C). These data suggest that ADA deficiency causes adenosine accumulation in lysosomes, which may further inhibit lysosome function, resulting in cell dysfunction.",
  "correct_citation": {
